			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">#1) I doubt this is out of malice to her ethnicity. Many schools have rules against hats, bandanas, etc, to get rid of distractions, and from fear of gangs. This was a case of a bit of strict rigid enforcement of the rules, without pausing to use common sence. That, or it was a fairness issue, with kids whining that she can wear her scarf, but they cant wear their Dallas Cowboy caps, or whatever.
<br />

<br />
#2) This ones pretty easy to refute. Your using a very obvious logical flaw, that minorites as an ethnic group break the law at exactly the same rate as whites. I'm not saying its a racial thing, its probably a class or economic thing. Poor people in general tend to break the laws more often than the wealthy. Now, take your racial numbers, find some numbers on their economic backgrounds, and scale them proportionately based on that.
<br />

<br />
If they get ticketed far more often, <span style="font-weight: bold">even when taking economic background in account</span> than white people, then fine you may finally have a valid arguement.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
