			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">First off cops are human beings so they have their own biases that influence how and when they happen to give tickets.  Are there cases of police officers harassing people for DWB or DWW (applies to the neighborhood of course)?  Yes, there are but even so it tends to be a difficult thing to prove because no one can read minds.  Of course perception is  stronger than fact, so if a group(s) of people believe they are being unfairly treated by the cops for example, you have a problem.
<br />

<br />
Second, rich people break laws just as often as poor people, the only difference is a rich person can afford the all star law team while a poor person is given a public defender.
<br />
  
<br />
This isn't to say all rich people have an automatic get out of trouble free card, but the better (and more expensive) your lawyer(s) the better you are in court as a defendant/plantiff.  
<br />

<br />
Do we honestly think poor trash are the only ones shoplifting?  Stealing money?  Speeding?  Smoking weed, shooing heroin or snorting cocaine?
<br />

<br />
The big difference is based on how the actual crime is committed.  A poor person in need of cash is more likely to commit a crime involving an element of violence to satisfy that need, ie robbing a bank / convience store.  A rich and educated person will most likely embezzle funds from their company to acquire the money they need.
<br />

<br />
The funny thing is, in the end both crimes are essentially the same; theft, they simply differ in how the theft was committed.  Yet robbing a convience store (with or without a weapon) and getting away with $100 yields more jail time typically than embezzling a $100k.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
