Yes they do. Your willing to say "OK, i agree that they probably steal, rob, sell more drugs", but that breaking the law in your car is some magical exception? BS, behind committing a crime, you have a motive to do so, whether its a motive to rob a bank, or a motive to do a 90 in a 55. Poor people in general are <span style="font-weight: bold">MUCH </span> more likely than wealthy to commit a traffic violation.
<br />

<br />
Maybe a few isolated redneck cops out there are quicker to arrest based on race. This contribution is very minute, compared to the overwhelming differences in economic background between the races. In general, the difference in tickets are not more often because of race. Minorities break the law legitimately, more often than whites simply because they have a larger proportion near or under the poverty line, and <span style="font-weight: bold">THAT </span> is where the causal relationship exists, <span style="font-weight: bold">NOT</span> race.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Second, rich people break laws just as often as poor people</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
No, they do not. This is very simply dead flat wrong. The numbers are not even remotely close, they are overwhelmingly lopsided. Your trying to tell me rich people hold up grocery stores, murder, DUI, etc JUST as often as poor people, but the enormous number of extra arrest rate on the poor is all explained away because of slick lawyers? Thats not possible, since the rich are not even arrested anywhere in the same planet in terms of rate as the poor. So lawyers dont even get involved.
<br />

<br />
We all get outraged by the isolated famous cases where a rich guy gets off with their million dollar lawyer. so it becomes "cool" to regurgitate out that rich people commit crimes just as much as everyone else, but they can buy themselves out. There are two problems with this line of thinking, which will be hard to grasp or accept from the left, because it flies in the face of their idea of human behavior. 
<br />

<br />
In general, the wealthy tend to be productive people who worked their ass off, followed all the rules, and earned their way to the top in life. In contrast, in general, the poor under the poverty line tend to be lazy, expecting a free ride from society, and little motivation to rise above the life they find themselves in. This mindset logically has a MUCH higher tendancy to selfishly try to take what they want from society. There's exceptions to every generality, some who are wealthy mostly lucked their way into it, or inherited, or worked for their wealth, but harbor serious mental problems that cause them to be criminals. Likewise, some poor are victims of a combination of spectacularly bad luck, struggling to rise but being slapped down by life over and over again. Generally though, wealth is not a random matter of winning life's lottery. There is a <span style="font-weight: bold">reason </span> why some people are successful. Their state of mind is not compatible with a desire to break the law. At least not as compatible as the mindset of the permenant apathetic underclass who I see every day week after week happily relying on their foodstamps and welfare, without a thought that they might be living a parasitic life.
<br />

<br />
The other problem is motivation. If you are wealthy, or even decent middle-class, what is your motivation to commit crime? IS it the same level  of motivation as those under the poverty line? Of course not.<span class="gensmall"></span>


