The constitution is not so cut and dried as you argue, it has some room to work with to make sence. The constitution doesnt allow government to establish or inhibit a religion or religious expression. However, when this need is met by another need, something has to give, and common sence usually dictates it. In this case, you have a need for kids to be in a learning environment where the school is free to remove flagrant distractions, thus you have dress codes, where the school is allowed to send you home to change from clothes that would be perfectly legal on the street, but a distraction at school. You also have safety issues with people banning items vaguely similar to the scarves, like bandanas, etc, for fear of gang affiliation and activity.
<br />

