			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><div class="postbody">The school is going to lose if this ever hits court...
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Oklahoma Statutes 253 wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">A. Except as provided in subsection B of this section, no governmental entity shall substantially burden a person’s free exercise of religion even if the burden results from a rule of general applicability. 
<br />

<br />
B. No governmental entity shall substantially burden a person’s free exercise of religion unless it demonstrates that application of the burden to the person is: 
<br />

<br />
1. Essential to further a compelling governmental interest; and 
<br />

<br />
2. The least restrictive means of furthering that compelling governmental interest</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Oklahoma Religious Freedom Act wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">7. "Substantially burden" means to inhibit or curtail religiously motivated practice.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">This is from the <a href="http://www.oscn.net/applications/OCISWeb/deliverdocument.asp?citeID=104672" target="_blank" class="postlink">Oklahoma statutes, section 253</a>, also known as the Oklahoma Religious Freedom Act. Before you decide to make some comments on it, you better look up what the phrases "compelling governmental interest," <span style="font-style: italic">strict scrutiny</span> and <span style="font-style: italic">ordinary scrutiny</span> mean. <span style="font-style: italic">Strict Scrutiny</span>, which is a fine word-of-art used by lawyers. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Word of art</span> is a legal phrase that means that the word or phrase is part of the technical terms of a field of endevour and does NOT mean what you think it means.
<br />

<br />
In short, strict scrutiny is the hardest possible burden to prove when trying to defend a law. Racial and sexual category legislation is generally held to be suspect and automatically gets strict scruitiny when they are challenged in court. There is a huge difference between <span style="font-style: italic">necessary state interest</span> (ordinary scrutiny) and <span style="font-style: italic">compelling state interest</span>. The state of Oklahoma has decided that restrictions on relgion require <span style="font-style: italic">strict scrutiny</span> in Oklahoma. Your state may be different.
<br />

<br />
Well, even though OKC is the buckle in the bible belt, kicking this kid out of school for worshipping the "wrong" religion, and displaying the acoutrements of that religion, will come back to bite them in the rear. Making a claim that christianity is the approved religion is an establishment of religion, also a Bozo-no-no. 
<br />

<br />
If you want to pretend to be fighting <a href="http://www.gangsorus.com/lettersa.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">gangs</a> by prohibiting colors, you better be prepared to ban red (the color of the Bloods) and blue (the color of the Crips). Will that stop folks from wearing the flag? It uses those 2 colors. Do folks predominantly wear things to the left (hats, earrings, keys)? Then they are/could be displaying a Bloods gang sign. Do they wear the stuff to the right? Then they are/could be displaying a Crips gang sign.<span class="gensmall"></span>


				</div></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
